    "cs01": {
      "abs": 1e-09,
      "rel": 5e-09,
      "tolerance_reason": "Self-test fixture: tolerance pinned to ~10x the worst observed deterministic FP residual on Finstack Quant's own calibrate + price round-trip. CS01 is the market-standard z-spread bump (the term-loan discounting pricer never consumes the hazard curve, so a par-spread/hazard bump leaves PV unchanged): the z-spread is solved to the quoted clean price (99.0% of notional), then bumped +/-1bp with a symmetric central difference. The Brent z-solve converges to 1e-10 on the spread axis and CS01's dependence on the anchor is second-order, so the value is deterministic to well within 1e-9; this band catches drift from refactors, FP-contract changes, or pricing-kernel algorithm swaps."
    }
